05336nam a22004815i 9780228005131DE-B159720230529094047.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||230529t20202020xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a97802280051317 a10.1515/97802280051312doi  a(DE-B1597)656712  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxccCA 4aRA450.4.I53.S53 7aSOC0620002bisacsh04a362.12231 aShaheen-Hussain, Samir, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aFighting for a Hand to Hold :bConfronting Medical Colonialism against Indigenous Children in Canada /cSamir Shaheen-Hussain. 1aMontreal ;aKingston ;aLondon ;aChicago : bMcGill-Queen's University Press, c[2020] 4cÂ©2020  a1 online resource :b8 illustrations, 4 maps  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aMcGill-Queen's Indigenous and Northern Studies ;v9700tFront Matter -- tContents -- tFigures -- tForeword -- tPreface and Acknowledgments -- tA Note to Readers -- tAbove All, Do No Harm -- tTimeline -- tIntroduction -- tMedevac Airlifts in Quebec and the Non-Accompaniment Rule -- tThe #aHand2Hold Campaign: Confronting a System -- tStructural Fault Lines in Health Care -- tSocial Determinants of Health: Equality, Equity, and Limitations -- tRecognizing Systemic Racism: A Social Justice Approach -- tMedical Culture and the Myth of Meritocracy -- tMedical Colonialism and Indigenous Children -- tA Little Matter of Genocide: Canada and the United Nations Convention -- tFrom the Smallpox War of Extermination to Tuberculosis Deaths in Residential Schools -- tExperimental Laboratories: Malnutrition, Starvation, and the BCG Vaccine -- tCruel Treatment: Indian Hospitals, Sanatoria, and Skin Grafting -- tGendered Violence: Forced Sterilization and Coercive Contraception -- tBreaking Up Families: Child Welfare Services, Mass Evacuations, and Medical Disappearances -- tOral Histories and the Narrative of Genocide -- tThe Structural Determinants of Health and Decolonizing Our Future -- tCapitalism and the Cost of Caring -- tHistory Matters: Colonialism, Land, and Indigenous Self-Determination -- tDecolonizing Health Care: Reparations before Reconciliation -- tConclusion -- tAfterword -- tReferences -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aLaunched by healthcare providers in January 2018, the #aHand2Hold campaign confronted the Quebec government's practice of separating children from their families during medical evacuation airlifts, which disproportionately affected remote and northern Indigenous communities. Pediatric emergency physician Samir Shaheen-Hussain's captivating narrative of this successful campaign, which garnered unprecedented public attention and media coverage, seeks to answer lingering questions about why such a cruel practice remained in place for so long. In doing so it serves as an indispensable case study of contemporary medical colonialism in Quebec. Fighting for a Hand to Hold exposes the medical establishment's role in the displacement, colonization, and genocide of Indigenous peoples in Canada. Through meticulously gathered government documentation, historical scholarship, media reports, public inquiries, and personal testimonies, Shaheen-Hussain connects the draconian medevac practice with often-disregarded crimes and medical violence inflicted specifically on Indigenous children. This devastating history and ongoing medical colonialism prevent Indigenous communities from attaining internationally recognized measures of health and social well-being because of the pervasive, systemic anti-Indigenous racism that persists in the Canadian public health care system - and in settler society at large. Shaheen-Hussain's unique perspective combines his experience as a frontline pediatrician with his long-standing involvement in anti-authoritarian social justice movements. Sparked by the indifference and callousness of those in power, this book draws on the innovative work of Indigenous scholars and activists to conclude that a broader decolonization struggle calling for reparations, land reclamation, and self-determination for Indigenous peoples is critical to achieve reconciliation in Canada.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Indigenous Studies.2bisacsh1 aBlackstock, Cindy, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGabriel, Katsi'tsakwas Ellen, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb40uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978022800513140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780228005131423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780228005131/original  aGBV-deGruyter-alles